                    {
                        "unit_id": 947,
                        "title": "Understand the Problem",
                        "slug": "understand",
                        "order": 20,
                        "status": "publish",
                        "content": "<div class=\"post-content\"></div>",
                        "media": {
                            "youtube_video_id": "9NV8j2egO0Q",
                            "banner_image_url": null,
                            "featured_image_url": null,
                            "pdf_template_url": null
                        },
                        "meta": {
                            "course-unit-read": "<h5>The first step in the innovation process is to <strong>understand the problem</strong> you’re trying to solve or the need that you are trying to address.</h5>\r\n<h5>To <strong>understand the problem</strong>, it’s good to put yourself in the shoes of the user or customer and empathize with them. You can do so by observing, surveying, and embedding yourself in the situation.</h5>\r\n<h5>In addition to understanding the problem from the user perspective, you can explore what are the current solutions available, what technology exists that could be used in solutions and where do they fall short in fulfilling the user needs.</h5>\r\n<h5>Understanding the problem and need is key to finding the right solution.</h5>",
                            "course-unit-read-more": "",
                            "course-unit-quotes": "<h5>\"When all think alike, then no one is thinking.\" - Walter Lippma</h5>",
                            "course-unit-case-study": "<h5>Natalie is tasked with the job of finding an innovative solution to reduce obesity in kids. For the first part of the innovation process, she seeks to understand the problem and why do kids get obese. Her aim is to understand the problem from all angles including the kids natural body composition, their emotional state, their surroundings, what influences them, where they live etc. Natalie also tries to understand what existing solutions have been used, what has their success been, what technologies exist today etc.. Natalie keeps on doing this investigative activity until she is quite confident that she has a good understanding of the problem at hand.</h5>",
                            "course-unit-last-related-content": "",
                            "course-unit-customrelated": "<ul>\r\n \t<li><a href=\"https://www.potential.com/articles/innovation-design-thinking/?utm_source=courses\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Innovation Design Thinking Process</a></li>\r\n</ul>",
                            "course-unit-page-show-game": "",
                            "course-unit-page-show-related": "",
                            "course-unit-page-ads": "",
                            "action_plan": "",
                            "templates_title": "",
                            "atq_btn": "",
